                            <p id="fs-idm25528064">
                              <span data-type="title">Check Your Learning</span>
                              What is the mass of 2.561 mol of gold?
                            </p>
                            <div data-type="note" id="fs-idm64655584">
                              <h3 class="os-title" data-type="title">
                                <span
                                  class="os-title-label"
                                  data-type
                                  id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                                >Answer:</span>
                              </h3>
                              <div class="os-note-body">
                                <p id="fs-idp11414864">504.4 g</p>
                              </div>
                            </div>
                          </div>
                          <div data-type="example" id="fs-idm8741648">
                            <h3 class="os-title">
                              <span class="os-title-label">Example</span>
                              <span class="os-number">2.9</span>
                              <span class="os-divider"></span>
                            </h3>
                            <p id="fs-idm24646960">
                              <span
                                data-type="title"
                              >Deriving Number of Atoms from Mass for an Element</span>
                              Copper is commonly used to fabricate electrical wire (
                              <a
                                class="autogenerated-content"
                                href="#CNX_Chem_03_02_copper"
                              >Figure 2.28</a>). How many copper atoms are in 5.00 g of copper wire?
                            </p>
                            <div class="os-figure" id="CNX_Chem_03_02_copper">
                              <figure data-id="CNX_Chem_03_02_copper">
                                <span
                                  data-alt="A close-up photo of a spool of copper wire is shown."
                                  data-type="media"
                                  id="fs-idm20298688"
                                >
                                  <img
                                    alt="A close-up photo of a spool of copper wire is shown."
                                    data-media-type="image/jpeg"
                                    id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                                    src="/resources/2822c5388c3a5e443ccc92c0290552c86152c2b4"
                                  >
                                </span>
                              </figure>
                              <div class="os-caption-container">
                                <span class="os-title-label">Figure</span>
                                <span class="os-number">2.28</span>
                                <span class="os-divider"></span>
                                <span class="os-divider"></span>
                                <span
                                  class="os-caption"
                                >Copper wire is composed of many, many atoms of Cu. (credit: Emilian Robert Vicol)</span>
                              </div>
                            </div>
                            <p id="fs-idm40043360">
                              <span data-type="title">Solution</span>
                              The number of Cu atoms in the wire may be conveniently derived from its mass by a two-step computation: first calculating the molar amount of Cu, and then using Avogadro’s number (
                              <em data-effect="italics">
                                N
                                <sub>A</sub>
                              </em>) to convert this molar amount to number of Cu atoms:
                            </p>
                            <span
                              data-alt="A diagram of three boxes connected by a right-facing arrow in between each is shown. The box on the left contains the phrase, “Mass of C u atoms ( g ),” the middle box reads, “Moles of C u atoms ( mol ),” while the one on the right contains the phrase, “Number of C u atoms.” There is a phrase under the left arrow that says “Divide by molar mass (g / mol),” and under the right arrow it states, “Multiply by Avogadro’s number ( mol superscript negative one ).”"
                              data-type="media"
                              id="fs-idm28023104"
                            >
                              <img
                                alt="A diagram of three boxes connected by a right-facing arrow in between each is shown. The box on the left contains the phrase, “Mass of C u atoms ( g ),” the middle box reads, “Moles of C u atoms ( mol ),” while the one on the right contains the phrase, “Number of C u atoms.” There is a phrase under the left arrow that says “Divide by molar mass (g / mol),” and under the right arrow it states, “Multiply by Avogadro’s number ( mol superscript negative one ).”"
                                data-media-type="image/jpeg"
                                id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                                src="/resources/a9625d7ac90586dd74e40910dac1631de5f1b937"
                              >
                            </span>
                            <p id="fs-idp18362672">
                              Considering that the provided sample mass (5.00 g) is a little less than one-tenth the mass of 1 mole of Cu (~64 g), a reasonable estimate for the number of atoms in the sample would be on the order of one-tenth
                              <em data-effect="italics">
                                N
                                <sub>A</sub>
                              </em>, or approximately 10
                              <sup>22</sup> Cu atoms. Carrying out the two-step computation yields:
                            </p>
                            <div data-type="equation" id="fs-idp20004432">
                              <math display="block">
                                <semantics>
                                  <mrow>
                                    <mrow>
                                      <mn>5.00</mn>
                                      <mspace width="0.2em"/>
                                      <menclose notation="horizontalstrike">
                                        <mtext>g</mtext>
                                      </menclose>
                                      <mspace width="0.2em"/>
                                      <mtext>Cu</mtext>
                                      <mspace width="0.2em"/>
                                      <mrow>
                                        <mo>(</mo>
                                        <mrow>
                                          <mfrac>
                                            <mrow>
                                              <menclose
                                                notation="horizontalstrike"
                                              >
                                                <mrow>
                                                  <mtext>mol</mtext>
                                                </mrow>
                                              </menclose>
                                              <mspace width="0.2em"/>
                                              <mtext>Cu</mtext>
                                            </mrow>
                                            <mrow>
                                              <mn>63.55</mn>
                                              <mspace width="0.2em"/>
                                              <menclose
                                                notation="horizontalstrike"
                                              >
                                                <mtext>g</mtext>
                                              </menclose>
                                            </mrow>
                                          </mfrac>
                                        </mrow>
                                        <mo>)</mo>
                                      </mrow>
                                      <mrow>
                                        <mo>(</mo>
                                        <mrow>
                                          <mfrac>
                                            <mrow>
                                              <mn>6.022</mn>
                                              <mspace width="0.2em"/>
                                              <mo>×</mo>
                                              <mspace width="0.2em"/>
                                              <msup>
                                                <mrow>
                                                  <mn>10</mn>
                                                </mrow>
                                                <mrow>
                                                  <mn>23</mn>
                                                </mrow>
                                              </msup>
                                              <mspace width="0.2em"/>
                                              <mtext>atoms</mtext>
                                            </mrow>
                                            <mrow>
                                              <menclose
                                                notation="horizontalstrike"
                                              >
                                                <mrow>
                                                  <mtext>mol</mtext>
                                                </mrow>
                                              </menclose>
                                            </mrow>
                                          </mfrac>
                                        </mrow>
                                        <mo>)</mo>
                                        <mspace width="0.2em"/>
                                      </mrow>
                                      <mo>=</mo>
                                      <mspace width="0.2em"/>
                                      <mn>4.74</mn>
                                      <mspace width="0.2em"/>
                                      <mo>×</mo>
                                      <mspace width="0.2em"/>
                                      <msup>
                                        <mrow>
                                          <mn>10</mn>
                                        </mrow>
                                        <mrow>
                                          <mn>22</mn>
                                        </mrow>
                                      </msup>
                                      <mtext>atoms of copper</mtext>
                                    </mrow>
                                  </mrow>
                                  <annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content">
                                    <mrow>
                                      <mn>5.00</mn>
                                      <mspace width="0.2em"/>
                                      <menclose notation="horizontalstrike">
                                        <mtext>g</mtext>
                                      </menclose>
                                      <mspace width="0.2em"/>
                                      <mtext>Cu</mtext>
                                      <mspace width="0.2em"/>
                                      <mrow>
